div.p:
VPon the expresse charge by the reformed Churches of this Kingdome and souer aigntie of Bearne, giuen to their Deputies, not to leaue the Assembly,

till by their most huble intreaties, and supplications to his Maiesly, they haue obtained contentment, vpon the iustice of their demands and complaints; the whole company hauing taken particular notice of the affaires concerning the Churches of France, and soueraignty of Bearne, and found the manifest danger that doth threaten them, if the effect of the Promises made vnto them, by the Patents, Declarations, Proclamations, & other Graunts and Concessions, as well of his Matesty now raigning, as of other Kings his Predecessors, wholly necessary to their subsistance, be not furthered, but hindred & delayed: Hauing also foud but too much by their former experience hitherto, that the iust & necessary things depending fro the execution, and performance of the said Patents, granted and promised to their Assemblies, and which by the dissoluing of them, haue beene committed to their generall Deputies neere his Maiesty, to sue for an answere, haue alwayes remained without any execution, by the art and cunning of their ill willers, who to this day haue hindred the effect of the good will & inclination of his Maiesty towards them. The company, I say in consequence of the Kings leaue for them so to meet, hath resolued and determined all with one voice, and vnanimous consent; where vnto also were found agreeable the aduices of the particular Deputies of the great Ones of the Religion, to stay together with the grace of God, & not to dissolue the Assembly, till they haue had a gracious answere to their iust demands and complaints;

with an execution and performance of such things as shall be promised, being necessary to the quiet estate and conseruation of the said Churches; who desire nothing els, but to finde their liberty, and safety, vnder the Authority and subiection of his Maiestie; submitting themselues euery one of the particular Deputies, as well of the Churches, and of the great Ones, composing the said Assembly, in case of any contradiction of their side, to this present Act and Article, to be declared Periurers, perfidious and detesters of the Vnion of the Churches; and vnworthy euer hereafter, to be seen in any generall, or Prouinciall Assembly. Giuen at Loudun the 7. of Decemb. 1619. Signed, The Vidame of Chartres President; Chaure his Adiunct; Maleray and Chalas Secretaries.
